      <bioghist id="aspace_ad38d0ec2cc708e480c89f1ab28d941a">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>One of the seven parties of the Yale Political Union, the Party of the Right was founded in 1953 by dissatisfied members of the original Conservative Party (later re-christened as the Independent Party) after that Party had endorsed Adlai Stevenson as "the conservative candidate for President." By the end of the 1950s many of the Party's enduring traditions had already been established, although it was not until the 1960s that the party really began to understand itself as "Conservatism reborn in Brotherhood." Due to a membership that included conservatives of every stripe, the Party found a dynamic tension between Libertarians and Traditionalists in the early 1970s that has been its hallmark for decades.</p>
         <p>Membership in the Party of the Right is elective and lasts "for life at least." Despite this promise, certain members disaffected by the political process left to form both the Tory and Conservative Parties of the Yale Political Union in 1971 and 1996 respectively.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_6cb686569de999cce66bf10c5fe72c11">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The materials consist of party correspondence, minutes, articles, research papers, debate materials, and a whip list.
There are also research papers, debate web sheets, party constitution, event ephemera, speeches, and news articles.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <relatedmaterial id="aspace_5d43736693cf50d09f57f4f987b433e0">
         <head>Related Materials Note</head>
         <p>Yale Political Union Records (RU 248).  Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </relatedmaterial>
      <arrangement id="aspace_809ecd4cea76f986d2ad9d94fae27c89">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The records are arranged by accession.</p>  
      </arrangement>
